Bring a #large pot{} of @salt{} water to a boil.

Meanwhile, wash and dry produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}(trimmed and thinly sliced), separating whites from greens. Zest and quarter @lemon{1}(zested and quartered).

Once water is boiling, add @spaghetti{6%oz} to #pot{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}.

Reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

While spaghetti cooks, pat @salmon{10%oz} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with half the @garlic powder{1%tsp}(divided), @salt{to taste}, and @pepper{to taste}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add salmon; cook until browned and cooked through, ~{5-7%minutes} per side.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #cutting board{} and tent with #foil{} to keep warm. Wipe out pan.

Once spaghetti is drained, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in pan used for salmon over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites and cook, stirring, until softened, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Stir in drained spaghetti, @peas{4%oz}, @cream sauce base{4%oz}, @Vidalia onion paste{½%oz}, remaining garlic powder, and a squeeze of lemon juice. Cook, tossing, until sauce has thickened and everything is evenly coated, ~{1-2%minutes}. (If sauce seems too thick, stir in reserved pasta cooking water a splash at a time.) Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Slice salmon crosswise.

Divide pasta between plates. Top with salmon, scallion greens, a squeeze of lemon juice, and as much lemon zest as you like. Serve with any remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> Fish is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.